src/features/admin/api/getUsers.ts

import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";
import { getAllUsers } from "../services/userService";

export async function GET(req: NextRequest) {
const users = await getAllUsers();
return NextResponse.json(users);
}

src/app/api/admin/users/route.ts

export { GET } from "@/features/admin/api/getUsers";

This keeps app/api clean and declarative, while the actual logic lives within the feature.
The same structure works for mutations, queries, and server actions.
The index pattern

Each feature exposes a controlled public surface via an index.ts file:

export _ from "./actions/createUserAction";
export _ from "./queries/useUsersQuery";
export _ from "./components/UserTable";
export _ from "./schemas/userSchema";

Then you can import everything you need with:

import { useUsersQuery, UserTable } from "@/features/admin";

This creates a clear boundary between what’s internal to the feature and what’s meant to be reused.
A mindset, not just a folder structure

Feature Driven Architecture is more than just a naming convention.
It’s a mindset that encourages modularity, ownership, and clarity.
It treats each feature as a small, autonomous product — something that could, one day, live on its own.

If you’ve ever opened a React project and thought “where does this logic actually belong?”, FDA gives you a consistent answer.

Organize by what your app does, not by what it’s made of.
That’s the core of Feature Driven Architecture.
